For those using SQLite, this DBMS doesn‚Äôt support Stored Procedures. For people using MySQL, the Stored Procedures is quite different. Below is the way how I did the first and second examples. Finally, there is no way to modify the parameters or the body stored procedure in MySQL, so you must drop it and create another one using DROP PROCEDURES IF EXISTS

Example 1
DELIMITER &&
CREATE PROCEDURE TEST ()
BEGIN 
SELECT * FROM Employee;
END &&
DELIMITER ;
CALL TEST;

Example 2
DELIMITER &&
CREATE PROCEDURE Test ()
BEGIN  
		DROP TABLE IF EXISTS Temp_Employee;
		CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE Temp_Employee (JobTitle VARCHAR (50), EmployeeperJob VARCHAR (50), Avg_Age INT, Avg_Salary INT );
		INSERT INTO Temp_Employee
		SELECT JobTittle, COUNT(JobTittle), AVG (Age), AVG (Salary)  
		FROM Employee emp INNER JOIN EmployeeSalary sal ON emp.EmployeeID = sal.EmployeeID
		GROUP BY JobTittle;
SELECT * FROM Temp_Employee;
END &&
DELIMITER ;
CALL Test;

